Citations
Date: 0/0/1937
Source: Dictionary of Slang
Author: PARTRIDGE
Vol / Page: 781
Edition:
Quote: <i>Sleep with Mrs Green</i>. To sleep in the open: New Zealand tramps' c. (- 1932). I.e. on the green grass. Cf. <i>Star Hotel. </i>
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1941
Source: NZ Slang
Author: BAKER
Vol / Page: 41
Edition:
Quote:  In later years we have records of the phrases <i>to sleep with Mrs Green</i> and<i> to doss in the star hotel,</i> used by tramps to describe sleeping in the open.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1949
Source: Dictionary of the Underworld
Author: PARTRIDGE
Vol / Page: 637
Edition: 1961
Quote:  To sleep in the open, e.g., in a park: Australian beggars' and tramps': since ca1920. Baker, 1942. I.e., on the grass; cf. the entry at Mrs. Ashtip.
Notes:

Date: 0/0/1988
Source: Dictionary of Kiwi Slang, A
Author: McGILL
Vol / Page: 104
Edition:
Quote: <i>sleep with Mrs Green</i> open-air slumber in tramp parlance, c.1932.
